TY  - JOUR
T1  - Improving Predictions in Expectancy Theory Research: Effects of Personality, Expectancies, and Norms
AU  - Miller, Lynn E.
AU  - Grush, Joseph E.
Y1  - 1988/03/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256500
DO  - 10.5465/256500
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 107
EP  - 122
VL  - 31
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study tested Fishbein and Ajzen's hypothesis that the behavior of some individuals will be rationally determined by personal expectancies and that the behavior of other individuals will be environmentally determined by social norms. As predicted, strong expectancy-behavior correspondence was obtained for individuals who were dispositionally aware of personal expectancies but unattuned to social norms. In contrast, we predicted and obtained strong norm-behavior correspondence for individuals who were dispositionally attuned to social norms but unaware of personal expectancies. Several methodological refinements in expectancy measures produced equivalent results.
AB  - This study tested Fishbein and Ajzen's hypothesis that the behavior of some individuals will be rationally determined by personal expectancies and that the behavior of other individuals will be environmentally determined by social norms. As predicted, strong expectancy-behavior correspondence was obtained for individuals who were dispositionally aware of personal expectancies but unattuned to social norms. In contrast, we predicted and obtained strong norm-behavior correspondence for individuals who were dispositionally attuned to social norms but unaware of personal expectancies. Several methodological refinements in expectancy measures produced equivalent results.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256500
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256500
