T1  - Impression Management: An Observational Study Linking Audience Characteristics with Verbal Self-Presentations
AU  - Gardner, William L.
AU  - Martinko, Mark J.
Y1  - 1988/03/01
PY  - 1988
DA  - 1988/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256497
DO  - 10.5465/256497
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 42
EP  - 65
VL  - 31
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study used direct observation to investigate the relationship between audience characteristics and the verbal self-presentational behaviors of 34 school principals. The results revealed that the principals presented themselves differently with high- and low-status, familiar and unfamiliar, and internal and external audiences. Differences in the principals' self-presentations during dyadic and group interactions were also observed. The implications of these findings for research on impression management behaviors and management theory are considered.
AB  - This study used direct observation to investigate the relationship between audience characteristics and the verbal self-presentational behaviors of 34 school principals. The results revealed that the principals presented themselves differently with high- and low-status, familiar and unfamiliar, and internal and external audiences. Differences in the principals' self-presentations during dyadic and group interactions were also observed. The implications of these findings for research on impression management behaviors and management theory are considered.
